				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I think it depends on the level of knowledge of the emulator author, and the types of emulated systems beforehand. <br /><br />As a newbie who started emulating about 7 months ago, and who literally did not know what a register or an instruction was about 8 months ago, I had an incredibly hard time getting started writing the NES emulator. I didn't understand why I was doing anything until a few months in, and even now, I only have a mostly-working CPU, and a semi-working PPU.<br /><br />Anyway, emulating the instruction set of a CPU should never be really hard. It's simply following a list and interpreting each instruction in a higher-level language, which is approximately the same for every CPU, but individual instructions are just more/less complex. I think the problem lies in little quirks that you can easily misunderstand or accidentally get wrong, like flags, modes (in case of ARM/8086 etc), individual cycles, external interrupts, and so forth. Looking at the ARM instruction set doesn't exactly make me shudder; it's all the things around it -- which are needed to make it a functional processor -- that scare me.<br /><br />I think the graphics processor's complexity depends on the system. The NES's PPU was quite hard for me to understand, and probably as much so for others who had no experience with it, but according to an x86 emulator author (miker00lz) in this thread: <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=3&amp;t=10495&amp;start=15" class="postlink">http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=3&amp;t=10495&amp;start=15</a>, emulating the x86 CPU was hard, but emulating a low-res VGA card (which can run the likes of Ultima and Doom mind you) was relatively simple compared to the NES's PPU. I guess it depends on what the system was made for. An early system built to run a multi-purpose home OS is apparently bound to have a complex processor but a pretty simple GPU.<br /><br />I can't tell you anything about sound, although I will say that I'm not planning to use any kind of library for my NES APU emulation. I'm writing the emu from scratch, so I guess I'll have a hard time getting that to work as well.<br /><br />All in all, it just depends on the system I suppose. CPU differs, GPU differs, but in general, if you have the knowledge, documentation (like Blargg said, very important if you don't want to spend half the time doing trial-and-error) and motivation, it's never far-fetched. Some assembly skill of the particular system helps IMMENSELY, at least it did help me. Of course you should keep in mind that even an emulator of something as relatively simple as an NES takes months/years to develop into something worthy of using, so it's never easy to write an emulator, it just gets easier with experience/knowledge.<br /><br />Sorry if it sounds like crap coming from a barely-experienced newbie <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /> this is all just from my point of view though.<br /><br />PS: You have like 5.5+k posts :O I thought you'd have written a dozen emulators by now. Maybe you have and this is just one of those curiosity questions? Who knows <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

