			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">To me, audio emulation is the hardest part. The CPU is pure logic, easy to trace and watch. The PPU is visual: I can tweak values and <em>see</em> when they're correct. Audio is just a huge crapshoot, and all the jargon around it boggles my mind.<br /><br />The PPU has pixels, tiles, sprites and attributes. I can visualize it all. The APU has periods, attack-decay-sustain-release, decimation, high-pass filters, low-pass filters, Nyquist limits, bass, treble, mids, equalizers, echo, frequency, decibels, windowed sinc, polyphase, band-limited synthesis, FIR filters, IIR filters, interpolation (gaussian, cubic spline, etc), DC bias, clipping, gain, impedance, reverb, on and on forever and ever. It's never explained step-by-step, instead you are given sigma notation expressions and expected to know enough calculus to make sense of it. Any time you do read up on it, every last person and article explains each thing completely differently.<br /><br />As far as overall, it highly depends upon the documentation. Great hardware documentation is like having the answer key to an exam. Without being given the answers, very minor details have taken me several weeks of research to figure out and exhaust all other possibilities (it's not just knowing one of many ways to simulate a behavior, but ruling out every possibility except for the correct one.)<br /><br />Experience plays a big role as well. My first emulator took a few months to run commercial games. My NES emulator took about 12 hours to fully run Super Mario Bros with no glitches. And again, documentation helped a lot there.<br /><br />At the end of the day, it's nothing special to be able to write emulators. A moderate IQ capable of programming, and a good bit of perseverance to keep at something until it works. The actual math and research steps are very basic, which is how someone of average intelligence like myself can get by. Of course, you can ramp up the difficulty all you like by targeting newer and newer systems.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

