				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Sep 19, 2004 9:28 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 1863<br /><b>Location:</b> Mountain View, CA, USA
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">ArsonIzer wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I guess I have something to look forward to then, if it's that simple. Also, I thought CGA was the most basic graphics adapter which runs on a DOS system. Why is it so difficult then? And why is a 16 color mode more difficult than a 256 color mode; Isn't that kind of backwards?</div><br />You're blindly (and incorrectly) assuming that because something is older that it's easier to understand/easier to deal with/easier to emulate.  This, in my experience, is rarely the case -- I find certain things that are older to be significantly more complex due to the fact that today's technology is made to be easier (many things are linear) while older technology tends to be less so due to financial/technological constraints at the time.  Things designed then were designed with very specific limitations kept in mind; things today are often designed with very different mindsets given how technology (hardware and software both) have improved and progressed over the years.  I will however say that the introduction of 3D into the marketplace has made a complete clusterfuck of KISS principle, but like the rest of this post, that's my opinion.<br /><br /><a href="http://webpages.charter.net/danrollins/techhelp/0089.HTM" class="postlink">CGA graphics are a &quot;packed pixel&quot;</a>, and the scanlines are non-linear (even lines start at a different base memory address than odd lines).  CGA also has all sorts of customisations you can set (bitmap vs. text mode) that make the thing a configurable, non-linear mess.  That doesn't even begin to touch on compatibility issues between CGA adapters.  CGA came out in 1980 or thereabouts.<br /><br />Compare that to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_13h" class="postlink">classic VGA 320x200 256-colour mode</a>, which out-of-the box (no &quot;register tweaks&quot; or things like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_X" class="postlink">&quot;Mode X&quot;</a> or the true/real way VGA works) where some of the memory layouts are packed or planar) is completely linear, a.k.a. &quot;mode 0x13&quot;: one byte per pixel in segment 0xA000, where each byte represents an entry in a palette that you can define the R/G/B values of yourself through some memory-mapped I/O registers.  VGA came out in 1986 or thereabouts.<br /><br />My advice to anyone considering an emulator: just stop.  If you really want to write one or tinker with one, particularly for the NES, <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Emulators#Under_development" class="postlink">look at this page</a> and then tell me inventing another one is worth the time and effort.  (Hint: it isn't.  Instead, what would be worthwhile would be getting rid of all the wonky bugs in existing emulators and making their UIs more user-friendly/sane.  It's remarkable how many shit the bed in various ways when you do something like click a menu while the emulator is running, etc.).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

