					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Sep 19, 2004 11:12 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 12423<br /><b>Location:</b> NE Indiana, USA (NTSC)
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><a href="http://webpages.charter.net/danrollins/techhelp/0089.HTM" class="postlink">CGA graphics are a &quot;packed pixel&quot;</a>, and the scanlines are non-linear (even lines start at a different base memory address than odd lines).</div><br />Scanlines in APA modes of NES, Game Boy, Genesis, and SNES are nonlinear in a different way. What happens in CGA is that the screen is broken up into tiles, much as on a console, but these tiles are 8x2 pixels. The second row of each tile is stored in high memory.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">CGA also has all sorts of customisations you can set (bitmap vs. text mode) that make the thing a configurable, non-linear mess.</div><br />It's even messier than the eight modes of SNES because a lot of games set up a composite color mode that uses Apple II-style artifact colors to get more than four colors on a screen.<br /><br />EGA is messy too because it has ports to control which planes get written, as well as semi-hardware-accelerated pixel data copies.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

