			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Thanks for the answer, a lot of different points of views.<br />To make things clear (esp. for Koitsu) I am not considering at all of writing a NES emulator, asking this might have implied that I was considering it but no, this was just to know how hard it is, no more, no less. I was maybe considering to be writing a CPU emulator for something completely different that has no relationship to the NES, so please don't think I'm stupid for asking this. Also it'd be nice if you would stop to complain that every single thing in the world sucks so hard and use swearing all the time, it'd be nice.<br /><br />@byuu, I perfectly get your point exactly. If some sample in sound emulation is wrong, it's unnoticeable just by ear, but if a pixel is wrong, you'll definitely notice it. If an instruction is wrong, any program using it will crash or behave incorrectly so it'll be easy to spot (assuming the program itself isn't packed with bugs <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> )<br /><br />@blargg, yes I perfectly get your point too, if you write an innacurate emulator, and then say &quot;oh s***t I want it to be accurate&quot; then you can't just improve it but have to re-think entirely how it is made internally.<br /><br />@ArsonIzer : Your viewpoint is very ineresting. You wanted to do an emulator without knowing anything about a CPU, that's a great achievement I'd have to say. And no a high post count doesn't mean I wrote multiple emulators, I never got interest for this. Like tepples I come here to develop games and tools (but the later only because there is a lack of tools on the market, so if I don't have a specific tool that does something I want to do I have to write it myself).<br />I only wrote 2 tools (3 in total but one of them isn't related to game development) and 0 games so far. Yes, 10 years of having this as a hobby, and 0 games. Yeah I suck. I have several half complete games though.<br /><br />@wendesday :<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">'The only thing hard about emulation is the documentation.'</div><br /><br />So this means if you emulate a perfectly documented system, it'll be extremely easy to emulate it ??<br /><br />Also, although all those answers are interesting, none of them really answers what I wanted to know. I'm sorry for being so annoying. I was more asking myself how is components like RAM, ROM and graphics are emulated.<br />Are they just huge char arrays in your code ? Or is there something I'm missing ?<br />How do you simulate a processor read that goes decoded to different peripherals ?<br />Is the screen emulated pixel by pixel or do you use openGL or some kind of hardware acceleration ?<br />How is the synchronisation between the various parts (CPU, GPU, APU) done ?<br />That's more of the stuff I was interested in knowing.<br /><br />Again I am not talking about the NES, but about systems in general (including systems which have nothing in common with a gaming console). Sorry for not being clear about it.</div>

