				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Mon Oct 13, 2008 7:55 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 976<br /><b>Location:</b> Minneapolis, MN
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">My advice to anyone considering an emulator: just stop.  If you really want to write one or tinker with one, particularly for the NES, <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Emulators#Under_development" class="postlink">look at this page</a> and then tell me inventing another one is worth the time and effort.  (Hint: it isn't.  Instead, what would be worthwhile would be getting rid of all the wonky bugs in existing emulators and making their UIs more user-friendly/sane.  It's remarkable how many shit the bed in various ways when you do something like click a menu while the emulator is running, etc.).</div><br />Good advice.  But I think part of the problem is that more obscure systems weren't as popular so nowhere near as many people flock to them to &quot;create an emulator of it so I can learn computer science&quot;.  Most of the new guys around here start out with &quot;I know not a lick of assembly language nor how to program in C or make a UI, but I thought it'd be cool to learn how to make a NES emulator...&quot;.  In the educational sense, it *is* worth the time and effort because there's a shitton of principles that can be learned from the exercise.  In practice, though, putting your creation on a page of &quot;NES emulators&quot; might be kind of like creating the &quot;flashlight app&quot; [an act which takes no specialized code beyond the instantiation of a new single view project in Xcode], and releasing &quot;your creation&quot; onto the App Store.<br /><br />The next part of the problem is there's too many goddamn UI toolkits.  Everyone has their favorite and wants to do something &quot;great/cool/spectacular&quot; in it to learn it.  But there again...learning a UI toolkit while writing a NES emulator means you'll have menus that malfunction and expected UI user experience that goes to /dev/null.  I'm as guilty of that as anyone else [started with MFC which I was 'fairly experienced in' -- moved to Qt and I'm *still* learning Qt].  But in the &quot;open source&quot; mindset, if you're trying to generate interest it's far better to get something out that has promise/potential that others can see how they might be able to improve/help, than it is to spit and polish alone.  Open source software hasn't quite hit the &quot;99 cent app wall&quot; that plagues app development...people don't necessarily expect perfection...and are largely patient with the authors ability to keep up with bug reports, etc.  I've taken a look at other emulators written in other UI toolkits and almost barfed...I'm sure people do the same about my emulator/IDE since Qt is just one way of skinning the UI cat.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

